[normal]Q1 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] 
[normal]Thank you very 
[normal]much
[normal]. You are all welcome. I would like to begin, if I may, with yesterday
[normal]’
[normal]s announcements on tariff changes. The Committee would like to understand where the thinking is about changes in the tariff. There is clearly 
[normal]a 
[normal]recognition that the previous structure was impeding efficient use of resources, response to demand and so forth. Should we see the changes announced yesterday as a long
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]term change or are they a fix to get us through the short term?
[normal]Professor Sir Bruce Keogh[bold]: 
[normal]Can I 
[normal]just 
[normal]give you some background to the thinking, Chair, because I was part of the NHS management board th
[normal]at considered these originally? 
[normal]Admissions had been rising at 4% to 4.4% per year for about eight consecutive years
[normal],
[normal] and we felt that acute trusts had no real incentive to h
[normal]elp keep people at home who didn’
[normal]t need to be in hospital. So we agreed to split the tariff in such a way that anything over the 2008
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]2009 baseline in terms of activity would only be paid for at 30% of the tariff rate
[normal];
[normal] the remaining 70% would be put into a pot and the trust would engage in discussion with commissioners on how that 70% could be used. That became effective in the operating framework for the NHS in 2010
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]2011.
[normal] 
[normal]Monitor subsequently reviewed that strategy to see whether it had any impact
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]W
[normal]hat we 
[normal]saw
[normal] almost immediately was a very rapid reduction to less than 1% in the growth of admissions.
[normal] 
[normal]What has been a bit more tricky
[normal], frankly, over the last three years during the transition has been to really work out whether that money has been actually used for that purpose. We are embarking on new measures to radiolabel that in a way that makes it absolutely identifiable. 
[normal]In May last year Barbara 
[normal]Hakin
[normal], as director of operations, wrote out to the urgent 
[normal]care 
[normal]working groups saying that they should have responsibility for ensuring how that money is used. You will recall from discussions last time that the urgent care working groups are, if you like, groups of people who have a vested interest in ensuring that local urgent care works properly
[normal]—
[normal]local authorities, commissioners, providers
[normal],
[normal] NHS England, Monitor and the TDA.
[normal] 
[normal]or 2014 we have clearly identified this money in the CCG budgets. We have determined that it should be used by the urgent care working groups
[normal],
[normal] and that will be assured by NHS England. 
[normal]One of the misconceptions that 
[normal]are
[normal] around is that all emergency admissions are being paid at only 30% of the rate. What it 
[normal]really 
[normal]amounts to in real terms is only 3% of the urgent admission activity. 
[normal]So, f
[normal]or the average trust
[normal],
[normal] we estimate that that would work out broadly 
[normal]in
[normal] the order of about £1.5 million. This is not something new and we will be looking at it over the course of the coming months.
[normal]Q2 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] 
[normal]Let me 
[normal]just
[normal] be clear. What is the scope, therefore, of this tariff if it is only 3% of admissions
[normal]? This is
[normal] not a tariff around emergency admissions
[normal].
[normal]Professor Sir Bruce Keogh[bold]: 
[normal]The idea was to try and reduce growth. Hospitals were already fully funded for activity at the 2008
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]2009 level
[normal],
[normal] and the idea was to try and stunt that growth so that it would not grow any further.
[normal]Q3 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] 
