[normal]The difficulty we have, and this will be 
[normal]part of the review
[normal], is that
[normal] we will look at all of these elements, but the A and E standard that we look to is four hours
[normal]. Now, that is
[normal] four hours to complete your treatment and be out of the door, 
[normal]to 
[normal]be transferred to another hospital if that is what you need, or to be admitted to an in
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]patient bed if you are one of the 20% or 25% that needs admitting. It is not a four
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]hour wait to be treated but four hours to have completed the whole of that episode. That is quite an achievement
[normal],
[normal] and, as Sir Bruce has said, it is the highest level of requirement internationally. The difficulty is that it is 95% of attendances. 
[normal]Across the country, if you go to A and E for an injury or an illness and you are then discharged straight home again, most patients complete that in under two hours. If you are 
[normal]admitted to hospital, the average is three and a half hours to be got into a bed. The difficulty is
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]because 
[normal]we use attendance as the denominator
[normal], and 
[normal]I talked about that seasonal variation where there is a lot of activity in the summer, which is a single il
[normal]lness or injury that goes home, 
[normal]it is relatively easy to hit the 95%. In the winter, when that activity melts away because people have stopped being so active and the number of elderly and frail patients and those with respiratory disorders climbs, the denominator has gone down but the numerator has climbed a lot, so it is very difficult to hit the 95%. 
[normal]That means that, going forward, we will have to look at things that are much more important to patients and clinicians other than a single target, which is what we have at the moment. Part of the review is that we will be working to look across the whole healthcare system to come up with measures that are far more meaningful and important to patients, to take away what can be some almost perverse incentives to perhaps deal w
[normal]ith patients in a way that doesn’
[normal]t feel right. Clinicians will always do what feels right for patients, but it does create pressures and I would fully accept that. So, going forward, as part of the review
[normal],
[normal] we have to change the standards we set so that they are broader and more patient and medically sensible.
