[normal] having critical care services or 
[normal]surgical s
[normal]ervices,
[normal] because there will not be an activity to make that safe or to keep staff there. So we would describe 
[normal]it as 
[normal]a hospital that has to be able to receive everything
[normal],
[normal] but for those patients who require the more specialist care
[normal],
[normal] over and above what the critical mass of the population can support
[normal] 
[normal]as a hospital
[normal]. T
[normal]hose patients will be moved on and that is part of the emergency network. It is not just receiving; it is the very rapid and safe identification and transfer of those patients. 
[normal]As you move towards a more urban area, your critical mass of population
[normal] increases and
[normal] the number of services that will be in the hospital will also increase, so the number of patients w
[normal]ho will need to be transferred—
[normal]rather
